      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While the push for civil rights was a powerful moral movement, the progress was far from inevitable; resistance was fierce and often violent. Many activists and thinkers within the movement debated strategy, with some advocating for more militant or self-defense approaches when nonviolent methods met extreme brutality. Furthermore, opponents actively worked to undermine the movement through legal challenges and political obstruction. Therefore, the passage of landmark laws was a hard-won result of sustained, strategic conflict, not a natural unfolding of events.",
      "source": "target",
